---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>

<Fragment slot="head-scripts">
  {schemaJsons.map((schema) => (<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />))}
</Fragment>

<ServiceHero
  eyebrow="Failure mode · Magnetron · HV Diode · HV Capacitor · Door Interlocks"
  title="Microwave Not Heating, Runs But Food Stays Cold"
  subtitle="Residential microwaves across LA, OC, Ventura, Riverside. High-voltage components require certified discharge protocol; capacitor stores 4kV even unplugged. $89 diagnostic, waived with repair. (424) 325-0520"
  heroImageTitle="Microwave Not Heating Repair"
  showBranches={true}
/>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · DIY safety warning</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The high-voltage capacitor stores 4,000 volts even after the unit has been unplugged for days.</h2>

    <p>This is not a YouTube DIY repair. The HV capacitor inside every traditional microwave stores about 4,000 volts of energy and holds that charge for hours, sometimes days, after the unit is disconnected from power. Touching the wrong terminal causes severe shock or death. We've seen the videos showing "easy magnetron swaps", we've also seen the customers who tried and ended up in the ER.</p>

    <p>Our techs follow a discharge protocol on every microwave service: short the capacitor terminals through a resistor before opening the high-voltage section. $89 diagnostic. We confirm which component failed (magnetron versus diode versus capacitor versus interlock) before any replacement, instead of swap-and-pray.</p>

    <p>BHGS #A49573, EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410), BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Magnetron failure (year 7 to 10, most common)</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Everything looks normal. Light, fan, plate rotation. No heat.</h2>

    <p>The magnetron is the component that actually produces microwave radiation. When it fails, you'll see all the surface signs of normal operation (cabinet light on, cooling fan spinning, turntable rotating, control panel responding) but the food stays cold. Year 7 to 10 is typical for a hard-use household; year 10 to 14 for light use.</p>

    <p>Replacement: $260 to $440 mid-tier countertop, $440 to $680 pro-style or built-in. Pro-style brands (Wolf, Miele, Thermador, GE Monogram, Sharp drawer) use OEM magnetrons with brand-specific mounting that costs more than the universal countertop replacements.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Panasonic inverter disambiguation</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Panasonic NN-SN and NN-SD use a different architecture entirely.</h2>

    <p>Panasonic NN-SN and NN-SD series (plus some Panasonic Genius-branded models) use an inverter board instead of the traditional magnetron-transformer-capacitor architecture. Newer Samsung models also use inverter on some lines. The symptoms look identical (microwave runs but doesn't heat) but the diagnostic tree is different.</p>

    <p>Traditional architecture failure tree: magnetron, then HV diode, then HV capacitor, then transformer, plus door interlocks. Inverter architecture failure tree: inverter board (which replaces the transformer and capacitor functions while driving the magnetron with variable-power output), then magnetron, plus door interlocks. Inverter board replacement runs $440 to $680, comparable to a magnetron + diode combination on traditional models.</p>

    <p>We identify by model number on the rating label before ordering parts. NN-SN and NN-SD prefixes are the tell on Panasonic; Samsung models with "inverter" in the marketing name use the same architecture.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Other failure modes</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Diode, capacitor, interlock switches.</h2>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>High-voltage diode.</strong> Rectifies 2,000V AC to DC for the magnetron. When diode fails, magnetron has no DC supply, no microwaves produced. $200 to $320.</li>
      <li><strong>High-voltage capacitor.</strong> Stores and smooths the high-voltage charge. Unstable failures cause intermittent heating; complete failure stops heating. $260 to $440. (Same component that holds the 4kV charge after unplug; DIY-unsafe.)</li>
      <li><strong>Door interlock switches (primary, secondary, monitor).</strong> All three must close in sequence before the magnetron is enabled. Worn switches at year 5 to 9 cause intermittent heating or no heating despite door appearing to close. $200 to $340 per switch.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real diagnostic stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · GE Profile OTR microwave, 8 years old</h3>
      <p>Magnetron failure, food cold despite all surface signs of normal operation. Discharged capacitor through resistor (40-second protocol), confirmed magnetron with multimeter, replaced. Total: $89 plus $310 magnetron plus 1.5 hours = $440. OTR repair pencils out at year 8; replacement OTR with install is $400 to $700.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Wolf MWD30 drawer microwave, 6 years old</h3>
      <p>HV diode failure (rare at year 6 but happens). Discharge protocol, isolated diode, replaced. Total: $89 plus $230 diode plus 1 hour = $310. Drawer microwave repair always justified given $2,800+ replacement.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · Sharp KB-6524 drawer microwave, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Magnetron plus capacitor (multi-component failure, common at year 9 on heavy-use units). Both replaced same visit. Total: $89 plus $640 parts plus 2 hours = $720. Sharp drawer at $1,800 to $2,400 replacement, repair justified.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Marina del Rey · Panasonic NN-SN686S countertop inverter, 11 years old</h3>
      <p>Inverter board failure. Quoted: $89 plus $480 inverter board plus 1 hour = $640. Customer math: replacement Panasonic equivalent $250 to $350 retail. Customer chose replacement. We charged $89 diagnostic, no parts, customer left with honest answer.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Calabasas · Miele M Touch built-in microwave, 7 years old</h3>
      <p>Door interlock primary switch worn (intermittent heating; sometimes worked, sometimes didn't). Plus HV diode degraded as confirmed by oscilloscope reading. Replaced both. Total: $89 plus $480 parts plus 1.5 hours = $640. Built-in Miele $3,200+ replacement, repair clearly the call.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06 · Repair vs replace by tier</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Honest math.</h2>

    <p><strong>Countertop ($150 to $300):</strong> magnetron failure year 6+ is a replace conversation. Repair cost $300 to $450 approaches new unit cost; year-6+ unit also has other components approaching end-of-life. Replace.</p>

    <p><strong>OTR ($300 to $700 unit installed):</strong> repair through year 10 to 12. Replacement OTR install runs $500 to $800 with electrical and venting; magnetron repair at $440 to $560 wins through year 10.</p>

    <p><strong>Pro-style or built-in ($1,500 to $4,000):</strong> Wolf MWD30 drawer, Wolf MC built-in, Miele M Touch, Thermador Masterpiece, GE Monogram, Sharp drawer. Repair always justified through year 15+. The cabinet integration and replacement complexity (sometimes requires cabinet refit) makes repair the obvious call up to multi-component failure.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">07 · Pricing</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What microwave-not-heating repair actually costs.</h2>

    <table class="price-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Service</th><th>Cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
